The democracy summit came to an end, and Biden said the flame of freedom would never be extinguished
The online Summit for Democracy, convened by U.S. President Joe Biden and attended by governments from 110 countries around the world and leaders of civil society and the private sector, ended on Friday (December 10).
In his closing remarks, Biden said the flame of freedom burns in the hearts of everyone in the world and that authoritarian regimes can never extinguish it.
He also said that he plans to hold a second global "democracy summit" next year.
Taiwanese government representative and political councilor Tang Feng and Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Lo Guan-chung, who is currently in exile in Britain, also spoke at the summit the following day.
Biden said: "We know how difficult the work ahead of us is.
But we also know that we can rise to the challenge because I have said before that, as this summit has shown, the democratic world is everywhere.
Authoritarian regimes can never extinguish the faint fire of freedom, which burns in the hearts of people all over the world and around the world. ”
Biden also said that defending democracy requires the joint efforts of the entire society.
"As leaders of government, we have a responsibility to listen to our citizens, to strengthen the guardrails of democracy, to push for reform, to achieve transparent and accountable governance, to be more resilient to the buffers and shocks of authoritarianism, and to those who want to pursue power nakedly before the public good," he said. ”
The themes of the second day of the Democracy Summit are defending human rights, consolidating democracy and confronting authoritarianism, and countering digital authoritarianism and affirming democratic values.
This day coincides with International Human Rights Day.
In his opening remarks on the day, UN Secretary-General António Guterres also said that the cause of democracy faces challenges around the world, especially those brought about by emerging digital technologies.
"It is time to reaffirm shared values and positions and democratic resilience," he said.
This requires deepening social dialogue, addressing inequalities, fighting corruption, renewing the social contract, investing in quality education, and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
It also requires a firm condemnation of populism, nativism and extremism in all its forms, including the use of all the tools offered by the technological revolution. ”
Speaking to the summit via pre-recorded video, Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Lo Guancong reminded participants of their continued attention to the human rights situation in Hong Kong and among Ethnic Chinese minorities such as Uighurs and Tibetans.
"For a long time, the world has been subject to China's rise without a mechanism to hold it accountable," he said.
That is why politicians and civil society leaders must cooperate.
We must use everything we have to ensure that the revival of democracy is our top priority. ”
Mr. Law also called on the free world to unite against the CCP's threat.
"Maybe some of you are afraid of upsetting General Secretary Xi Jinping, maybe some of you don't want to lose the Chinese market, maybe some of you don't recognize the threat to our democratic values," he said.
And that's why we failed.
That's why we have to change . ”
Tang Feng, a political councilor of Taiwan's Executive Yuan, released a "National Declaration" via video during a roundtable discussion on "Cracking Down on Digital Authoritarianism and Affirming Democratic Values," stressing that Taiwan stands at the forefront of the fight against authoritarianism and authoritarianism.
He also shared his experience in how to combat COVID-19 through transparency and building trust.
"At a time when Taiwan's democracy is in its infancy, we have always stood firmly at the forefront of the global fight against authoritarianism, and have played a leading role in promoting global freedom, democracy and human rights," he said.
During the pandemic, authoritarian governments everywhere have justified human rights abuses in the name of public health and collective interests, and global democracy is showing signs of regression.
However, in Taiwan, we don't have to lock down the city to control the epidemic, and we don't have to take down the shelves to defeat false information. ”
At the same time as the second day of the Democracy Summit, the U.S. Treasury Department announced sanctions against 15 individuals and 10 entities in several countries, including China and North Korea, which have been found to have committed serious human rights violations, as well as investment restrictions on a Chinese company found to have used surveillance techniques to assist in human rights violations.
