Vietnam People's Daily - GCC addresses common challenges
Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman's stops include Oman, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain and Kuwait.
Notably, this is Crown Prince Mohammed's first visit to Qatar since Saudi Arabia and its Arab allies imposed an embargo on Qatar in mid-2017, leading to a diplomatic crisis in the Gulf.
In the midst of the crisis, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain and Egypt have severed diplomatic relations with Qatar and imposed a sweeping embargo on it, accusing Qatar of supporting terrorist groups and having close ties with Iran.
Diplomatic tensions have seriously affected the internal unity of the GCC and have had a negative impact on the economies of countries in the region.
Four Arab countries blocked land, sea and air routes to Qatar.
The crisis was resolved only at the GCC summit in January 2021, when the Gulf states signed an agreement to move toward "unity and stability" mediated by the United States and Kuwait.
Saudi Arabia has reopened its borders with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are taking the lead in efforts to restore relations with Qatar through the appointment of new ambassadors in Qatar by both countries.
The Gulf Arab States resolved their differences in order to restore relations with Qatar out of a demand that must be united for the interests of all countries and regional stability, aimed at addressing common challenges.
During the Saudi crown prince's visit to Oman, the two sides agreed to open the first direct land route between the two Gulf neighbors.
The 725-kilometre-long corridor connecting the two countries will facilitate mobility and integrated supply chains for citizens of both countries.
The Saudi Arabian Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest $5 billion in Oman, and companies from the two countries have signed 13 memorandums of understanding on cooperation worth $30 billion.
The Saudi crown prince's visit to the Gulf states coincided with negotiations between Iran and the world's major powers to save the Iran nuclear deal known as the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA) — an agreement condemned by gulf Arab states for arguing that they could not resolve the missile issue with Iran.
Gulf states have long viewed Iran as a long-term "competitor" and iran's nuclear program as a "threat" to regional security.
Gulf states believe that there is a flaw in not addressing the Iranian missile issue and not taking action to curb Iranian activities in the region.
Saudi Arabia has negotiated directly with Iran against the backdrop of the failure of the major powers to meet the wishes of the Gulf states.
Its goal is to contain the escalation of tensions in the region.
This is one of the factors slowing the economic growth of the GCC countries.
The upcoming GCC summit will be the first GCC summit since some members ended their dispute with Qatar.
This is an opportunity for the GCC to reassess the diplomatic achievements that have contributed to the restoration of the unity of the GCC, while proposing measures to enable its member States to cooperate fully in meeting common challenges and contributing to the stability and development of the Gulf States.
